ğŸ› Challenges & Fixes
Issue: No logs appearing in Splunk
Root Cause: Receiving port not properly enabled initially
Fix: Enabled receiving on port 9997 and restarted Splunk
ğŸ¯ Outcome

ğŸš¨ Problem

Windows Security Event Logs were not appearing in Splunk Enterprise, even though:

Splunk Universal Forwarder service was running

splunk list forward-server showed Active
_internal logs from the client were visible
Security events were present in Event Viewer

Search query returned no results:

index=wineventlog host=<clienthostname>
ğŸ” Investigation Steps

Verified forwarder service status (services.msc)

Confirmed active connection using:

splunk list forward-server

Verified receiving port 9997 on Splunk Enterprise

Confirmed _internal logs were being received

Checked inputs.conf configuration

Ran:

splunk list inputstatus

No WinEventLog inputs were listed.

ğŸ¯ Root Cause

The configuration file was incorrectly saved as:

inputs.conf.txt

Due to Windows hiding file extensions.

Splunk only loads files ending strictly in:

.conf

As a result, the Universal Forwarder did not load the WinEventLog input configuration.

âœ… Resolution

Enabled "File name extensions" in Windows Explorer.

Renamed file from:

inputs.conf.txt

to:

inputs.conf

Restarted Splunk Universal Forwarder:

splunk restart

Verified WinEventLog inputs were loaded:

splunk list inputstatus

Confirmed logs successfully appeared in Splunk Enterprise.

ğŸ§  Lessons Learned

Always verify file extensions on Windows systems.

Use splunk list inputstatus to confirm inputs are loading.

_internal logs can confirm connectivity even if data inputs fail.

Structured troubleshooting prevents unnecessary configuration changes.
Established a functional SIEM ready to receive endpoint logs.
